<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFrameworks>net8.0;net10.0</TargetFrameworks>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <PackageId>FluxFlow.Components.Mqtt</PackageId>
    <AssemblyName>FluxFlow.Components.Mqtt</AssemblyName>
    <RootNamespace>FluxFlow.Components.Mqtt</RootNamespace>
    <Version>3.0.0</Version>
    <Authors>FluxFlow contributors</Authors>
    <Description>Standalone MQTT nodes for FluxFlow over an injected client adapter: a connection handle that owns the client lifecycle (host-driven connect/disconnect), publish (request in, result out) and subscribe (received messages out) nodes that borrow the established adapter, and an MQTT5 request/reply trigger (MqttRequestContext + the transport-neutral RequestReplyCoordinator). One package for the whole MQTT surface — connection, publish, subscribe, and trigger. Broadcast output/error/event ports. No engine required.</Description>
    <PackageTags>workflow;dataflow;components;mqtt</PackageTags>
    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>
    <PackageReleaseNotes>Rebuilt as standalone nodes over the FluxFlow.Nodes kit: the engine and designer dependencies are removed. mqtt.connection becomes a self-contained connection handle (IMqttConnectionHandle) that owns the single client lease, epoch, health monitor, and host-driven ConnectAsync/DisconnectAsync lifecycle, exposing connection health on a broadcast FlowEvent port; the carefully hardened gate/single-flight/lease-ordering/dispose-race concurrency is unchanged. mqtt.publish becomes a FlowNode (MqttPublishRequest in, MqttPublishResult out) and mqtt.subscribe a FlowSource (MqttReceivedMessage out); both borrow the established adapter when connected (subscribe (re)subscribes per connection epoch) and report not-connected on the error port otherwise, never connecting or disposing. NodeAddress is dropped; the connection identity is its ConnectionName. The node registration module, factories, ports, options reader, component types, and design-metadata provider are removed. Contracts, options, topic validation, and diagnostics are preserved. The MQTT request/reply trigger (formerly the separate FluxFlow.Components.Mqtt.RequestReply package) is now folded into this single MQTT package: MqttRequestContext writes the correlated reply to the MQTT5 response topic via a host-supplied IMqttResponsePublisher, driving the transport-neutral RequestReplyCoordinator.</PackageReleaseNotes>
    <RepositoryType>git</RepositoryType>
    <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>
    <IncludeSymbols>true</IncludeSymbols>
    <SymbolPackageFormat>snupkg</SymbolPackageFormat>
  </PropertyGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <ProjectReference Include="..\FluxFlow.Nodes\FluxFlow.Nodes.csproj" />
    <ProjectReference Include="..\FluxFlow.Components.RequestReply\FluxFlow.Components.RequestReply.csproj" />
  </ItemGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="System.Threading.Tasks.Dataflow" Version="9.0.4" NoWarn="NU1510" />
  </ItemGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <None Include="README.md" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
